Just 2 days left until the meetup in Lisbon!🔜📢
How can routine legal matters bring joy to Web3 teams? And why was the decision made to integrate a legal tech startup into Telegram? We met with a speaker and recorded a short interview:

🖇️Artem Afian, CEO of Delegate Bot, is a first-wave crypto lawyer and a legal tech entrepreneur. He is a well-recognized lawyer practising in Ukraine and a member of the World IT Lawyers Association.

What are the top 3 main mistakes/stereotypes of web3 teams regarding legal aspects?
Thinking that legal is unimportant and can wait. I can say that legal matters are as important as choosing a tech layer. In fact, companies and projects should pay attention to legal issues from day 1.

Why was the decision to create a bot specifically on Telegram and on TON?
First of all, because of its technological capabilities. Cool web apps are an interesting part of the ecosystem. The ecosystem is still developing, and the most interesting part involves trying to build something inside a super app. That’s the main challenge because we don’t want to create a separate ecosystem; we want to be integrated into something significant. That’s why TON.

Contracts: where does the pain end and the pleasure of using begin?
The main pain of contracts is that nobody understands them. All this works as an ancient ritual. We take obligations by carwing them on pieces of wood with signs we do not understand. All of this can be reimagined.

Will it be possible to test one of these contracts directly at the meetup 17.08?
Of course, we can sign it during the event. I'll show how it works, and I hope everybody will have fun. Let's see how legal can bring joy:)

📅17.08 ⌚19.00 📍grow.inc SPACES

Don'‎t forget to reserve your tickets and check the agenda HERE. See you at the TON Society Europe meetup💎

Kathleen Olstedt
Hello fellow Web3 folks,

As Lisbon becomes more popular and we (most of us tech immigrants and expats) do our part to gentrify this city, it's time to think about how we can bridge the gap.

Before, I've lived in Berlin for 20 years and have witnessed firsthand the transformation from a city of artists and culture to a city where large corporates plaster innovation labs on every corner.

It was 2012 when a few New-Berliners got together and decided to "Give something back to Berlin" - a movement in which they started to get involved in local initiatives… slowly building these needed bridges.

It would be great to start something similar here in Lisbon.

I have been working on bringing Web3 primitives to local communities for almost a year now. I'm very confident that we will not only be able to provide valuable hands-on support, but also do it in an efficient way.

If anyone is interested in this, please send me a dm, so I can invite you to the group and we can get started!

The Ultimate List of Crypto Debit Cards (Alphabetical Order)

Augment Labs - https://card.augmentlabs.io
• Pro: Spend at any merchant that accepts Visa, can use worldwide
• Con: High fees (3-3.5% fee to load the cards), utilises USC (their own stablecoin lel)

Basedapp - https://basedapp.io/
Free for now, usual price $19
• Pro: Spend at any merchant that accepts Visa, account abstraction, up to 1% cashback
• Con: Supports only Singapore registrations and XSGD at the moment

Gnosis Pay - https://gnosispay.com/
Costs 30 EUR
• Pro: Self Custodial Visa Debit Card, spend at any Visa Merchant. Funds linked to SAFE L2. Transfer funds from any EVM and token
• Con: Currently available only in Europe and supports only EURe

HolyHeld - https://holyheld.com/
Costs 29 EUR
• Pro: Virtual Card, 1% daily cashback for metal cardholders, else 0.5% cashback in USDC. Supports Apple Pay & Google Pay. Get personal IBAN
• Con: Currently available only in Europe

Monolith - https://monolith.xyz/
• Pro: 0% transaction fee (on all stable coins and TKN)
• Con: Currently available only in Europe, New Card Applications currently unavailable

Plutus - https://plutus.it/
• Pro: Non-custodial Card (Future), Earn 3% in crypto (PLU tokens), Virtual and Physical Cards available
• Con: Currently only supporting UK and Europe, Contactless payment trxs have a limit of 50 EUR/GBP per trx, 90 EUR/GBP daily

Stables - https://stables.money/
• Pro: Great UI/UX, supports multichain, spend anywhere Mastercard is accepted. Send stables to friends. Earn (Future)
• Con: Currently supporting only Australians. 0% fee, but considerable spread when spending USDC intl.

Wirexapp - https://wirexapp.com/
• Pro: Up to 8% cashback in native tokens. Earn on crypto in x-accounts. Supports cross-chain. No fee.
• Con: To get highest tier of cashback, you need to join their subscription plan ($30 per month)

Zebec - https://zebec.io
Launching in Fall in Select Countries
• Pro: Seamless conversion from Metamask Wallet
• Con: It's not a traditional credit/debit card, but rather a gift card

Credit Card
Gemini - https://www.gemini.com/credit-card
• Pro: Earn rewards in other cryptos, get cashback on different spends, no annual fee
• Con: Only available in the US

Not Yet Launched
Bleap - https://www.bleap.finance/
Kulipa - https://kulipa.xyz/
Palladium - https://palladium.co/

B2B Cards (For companies that want their own branded cards)
Alchemy Pay - https://alchemypay.org/crypto-card
Immersve - https://immersve.com/
Reap - https://reap.global/
Striga - https://striga.com/
